"\n# Briefing NEM TEST self-test\nLast update: June 16, 2026\nStatus: Phase B - Ready for review Will\nScope:\nTechnical briefing for Will for the build of NEM TEST self-test \"Waarom reageer ik zo?\" in Webflow.\nPhase A of this build is complete — the MVP has been delivered. We are now moving into Phase B. This phase covers the full production build: landing page, question module, conclusion screen, report offer flow, and backend integration. The sections below are structured accordingly. Phase A documentation is preserved at the bottom of this document for reference.\nRelated documents:\nNEM TEST source — 375c706b-69c0-8081-9ce5-e847ebb46b6c\nNEM TEST Waarom reageer ik zo? — 37bc706b-69c0-811c-b7a8-e7af96b8e720\nChange log:\n2026-06-14: Document restructured into Phase A (reference) and Phase B (active build). Phase B sections added as scaffolding. OTP verification approach replaced — see section D. Document language corrected to English throughout.\n2026-06-12: First test will be named \"Waarom reageer ik zo?\"\n2026-06-04: Added list of 20 questions.\n2026-04-30: Initial document setup.\n\n## Phase B - Production build\n\n## B1 - Landing page\n\n### Hero & Navbar\nHybrid version.\nLogo left (clickable, links to homepage)\nTrust anchor right: \nsmall portrait photo of Christel\nText \"Christel Reus - therapeut & ontwikkelaar van de NEM Methode\".\nsmall portrait photo of Christel\nText \"Christel Reus - therapeut & ontwikkelaar van de NEM Methode\".\nNo navigation links. No menu. No other distractions.\nLanding page header height (Will, input needed)\nI suggest we use the current header (as used on the NEM Methode page) but important: the first question of the test should be visible above the fold without scrolling. Both on desktop and mobile.\n\n### Full copy\nH1-headline:\nJe reageert anders dan je wil. Steeds opnieuw.\nH2-heading:\nIn 5 minuten zie je welke reactie jou het meest vasthoudt.\nPromise line:\nNa de test ontvang je een persoonlijk rapport in je mail - gratis.\nBelow H2-heading. A bit smaller, font, as H2-heading needs to be more dominant.\n<NEM TEST question-module>\nDisclaimer:\nDeze test is geen psychologische diagnose. Het is een spiegel op basis van jouw antwoorden - bedoeld als beginpunt voor reflectie, niet als eindoordeel.\nSmall font, light colour.\nPermanent placement below NEM TEST question module.\n\n### Footer\nWe want to introduce a minimal footer variant for all landing pages, including NEM TEST tests. Each landing page should be conversion-focused. A full footer with navigation columns gives our visitor/user too much exit points and distraction. The minimal footer keeps the page legally compliant.\nNEM Life logo (clickable, links to homepage)\n\n## B2 - NEM TEST question module\nThe question module is the core of the test experience — it runs from the first question through to the conclusion screen and governs all UX behaviour, score tracking, and screen transitions in between.\n\n### Screen 1 - Start\nPreview:\nProgress indicator:\nVraag 1 van 20 (EN:Question 1 of 20)\nQuestion 1 (start question):\nAls iets in een relatie of op het werk misgaat, ben ik de eerste die denkt dat het aan mij ligt.\nRe-assurance line:\nKies wat het meest op jou lijkt - er is geen goed of fout antwoord.\nShown on screen 1 only - does not repeat on subsequent questions\nAnswer values:\nnooit | zelden | soms | regelmatig | heel vaak\nHorizontal pill buttons - default state: white fill, dark border. when hoovering: colour effect.\nMobile: five buttons stack vertically, full card width. No horizontal layout on mobile.\n\n### Screen 2 - Questions\nPreview:\nProgress indicator:\nAd back arrow (←). Small, muted, arrow only — no label text.\nOn click: returns to previous question with previously selected answer pre-filled.\n\n### Screen 3 - Conclusion\nPreview:\nLabel Jouw uitkomst\nStatic text. Same muted colour as the progress indicator in the question module — not a primary heading.\nConclusion\nThe conclusion text is dynamically generated by Claude based on Anna's score profile. This is not a static text — it changes per user.\nThe placeholder (Lorem ipsum) in the design represents two paragraphs of personalised copy. Do not hardcode any text here.\nBridge line\nWil je begrijpen waar dit vandaan komt en wat het jou kost? Je persoonlijke rapport gaat daar dieper op in.\nThis sentence carries conversion weight and should not be visually downplayed.\nCTA button:\nOntvang mijn rapport\nIt does not submit anything - it only opens the next screen.\n\n### Screen 4 - Opt-in\nPreview:\nLabel:\nWaar sturen we jouw rapport naartoe?\nIntroduction line:\nVul hieronder je gegevens in. Je ontvangt het binnen enkele minuten in je inbox.\nForm fields:\nVoornaam (EN: First name) | E-mailadres | Je relatiestatus (EN: Your relationship status)\nJe relatiestatus\" is a dropdown select element. Fixed options: Alleenstaand (EN: Single) / In een relatie (EN: In a relationship) / Gescheiden (EN:Divorced) / Anders (EN: Other)\nAll 3 fields and email opt-in (see below) are required. Validation fires on submit.\nWill, is it possible in Webflow to immediately validate the email address (on blur?) when the submitter leaves the field?\nOpt-in NEM Matters:\nJe wordt toegevoegd aan NEM Matters - de nieuwsbrief van NEM Life. Je kunt je altijd afmelden.\nThe \"Ontvang mijn rapport\" button remains inactive (greyed out, not clickable) until the checkbox is ticked. No submission without explicit consent.\nError handling\nWill, is the following process easy to arrange?\nOn failed validation: field border turns red. A short inline error message appears directly below the field in small red text. The card does not reload. Fields already correctly filled remain untouched. Once a field is corrected, the red border clears immediately — no resubmit needed to remove the error state.\nInline error messages:\nVoornaam (empty): \"Vul je voornaam in\"\nE-mailadres (empty): \"Vul je e-mailadres in\"\nE-mailadres (invalid format): \"Voer een geldig e-mailadres in\"\nYour relationship status (not selected): \"Selecteer je relatiestatus\"\nCheckbox (unticked): \"Bevestig je aanmelding voor NEM Matters\"\nVoornaam (empty): \"Vul je voornaam in\"\nE-mailadres (empty): \"Vul je e-mailadres in\"\nE-mailadres (invalid format): \"Voer een geldig e-mailadres in\"\nYour relationship status (not selected): \"Selecteer je relatiestatus\"\nCheckbox (unticked): \"Bevestig je aanmelding voor NEM Matters\"\nCTA:\nButton text: Ontvang mijn rapport\nRelieve line: Geen spam & je gegevens blijven veilig. Natuurlijk.\nSubmit button state\nOn submit attempt with errors: button does not trigger the backend. Errors appear in place. \nOn successful validation: button enters a brief loading state (spinner or slight opacity reduction) to prevent double submission. Transition to screen 5 follows on successful backend response.\nOn submit attempt with errors: button does not trigger the backend. Errors appear in place.\nOn successful validation: button enters a brief loading state (spinner or slight opacity reduction) to prevent double submission. Transition to screen 5 follows on successful backend response.\nDisclaimer:\nDit rapport is geen psychologische diagnose. Het is een spiegel op basis van jouw antwoorden - bedoeld als beginpunt voor reflectie, niet als eindoordeel.\n\n### Screen 5 - Confirmation\nPreview:\nGeneral note:\nThis screen is static. No dynamic content.\nLabel:\nNog één stap\nMuted colour, same treatment as \"Jouw uitkomst\" on screen 3.\nLines:\nJe antwoorden zijn opgeslagen. Zodra je je e-mailadres bevestigt, stellen we jouw persoonlijke rapport samen en sturen we het naar je inbox.\nControleer je inbox - je ontvangt direct een mail van NEM Life. Klik op de bevestigingslink daarin en je rapport is onderweg.\nFallback lines (smaller font, muted colour, below main copy):\nGeen mail ontvangen? Controleer je spamfolder.\nVerkeerd e-mailadres opgegeven? Vul het opnieuw in.\n\"Vul het opnieuw in\" must be a clickable link. \nOn click: returns Anna to screen 4 with Voornaam and relationship status pre-filled. E-mailadres field is cleared so she only needs to correct that field. On resubmit, a new confirmation email is triggered and the previous token is invalidated.\n\"Vul het opnieuw in\" must be a clickable link.\nOn click: returns Anna to screen 4 with Voornaam and relationship status pre-filled. E-mailadres field is cleared so she only needs to correct that field. On resubmit, a new confirmation email is triggered and the previous token is invalidated.\n\n## B4 - Backend process\nWill, this section outlines our current thinking on the backend flow. We'd like your input before locking anything down — please share your feedback on feasibility and approach.\n\n### Overall architecture\nWe're thinking in two separate triggers, intentionally decoupled. Nothing expensive happens (no report generation by Claude) until the user has verified their email.\nTrigger 1 - Form submission (screen 4)\nWhen the user submits the opt-in form, we'd like Webflow to pass her score profile and form data to n8n.\nn8n stores this temporarily and instructs MailerLite to send a verification email. No report is generated at this stage — no Anthropic API call, no PDF, no cost.\nData we'd want to store at this point:\nscore per mechanism (5 values),\nfirst name,\nemail address,\nrelationship status,\nand a unique token tied to this submission.\nTrigger 2 - Verification link click\nWhen Anna clicks the link in the verification email, n8n picks up the token, retrieves the stored score profile, calls the Anthropic API to generate the personalised report, converts the output to PDF, and sends it as a direct attachment via MailerLite. If Anna never clicks, nothing happens.\n\n### Report delivery\nPDF as direct email attachment — no download page. One tap to forward, no extra steps for Anna.\n\n### NEM Matters opt-in\nThis runs as a separate flow from the report delivery. Anna's consent is captured on screen 4 — the actual MailerLite subscription is processed independently, not bundled with the report trigger.\n\n### Analytics & conversion tracking (Phase C - not in scope for current build)\nWe want to track key conversion events in a future phase. No implementation needed now, but we'd ask you to name the events in the code already so they're easy to hook up later.\nEvents to label:\nTest completed — Anna answers question 20 and the conclusion screen appears.\nReport requested — Anna submits the opt-in form on screen 4 (successful submission).\nEmail verified — Anna clicks the verification link (trigger 2 fires).\nEmail not verified — token expires without trigger 2 firing.\nWe'll decide on the tracking tool separately.\n\n### Questions for Will\nIs the two-trigger architecture feasible with our current Webflow + n8n setup?\nWhere do you suggest storing the score profile between trigger 1 and trigger 2 — n8n internal storage, a Webflow CMS entry, or something else?\nAny concerns about token management and expiry?\nWe want to keep this build as lean as possible — both in complexity and cost. Please indicate for each part of the backend which elements you handle yourself, and where you'd recommend bringing in a specialist.\nFor reference: we have a freelancer available who specialises in n8n, and a separate specialist for MailerLite. We leave it to you to advise where their involvement would add value.\nFor reference: we have a freelancer available who specialises in n8n, and a separate specialist for MailerLite. We leave it to you to advise where their involvement would add value.\n\n## Phase A - MVP reference\nThis is the original briefing on which the MVP was built. Preserved here for reference. Phase B specifications above supersede and refine this content where applicable.\n\n## A1 - Introduction - What is NEM TEST\nNEM TEST is a suite of reflective self-tests within the NEM Life ecosystem.\nEach test consists of a series of questions scored on a 1–5 scale.\nThe total score is calculated by summing all question scores.\nBased on the final total score, the participant receives a personalised result. The report is dynamically generated by Claude via the Anthropic API — not pre-written per outcome category.\nThe tests are designed to support recognition and reflection, not diagnosis or classification.\n\n## A2 - Purpose of this briefing\nThis document defines a reusable template for designing and implementing NEM TEST self-tests. The goal is to build a scalable framework capable of supporting at least 10+ structured self-tests over time.\nIt describes the intended structure, UX approach, and functional requirements, independent of specific test content.\nThe goal of this document is to ensure consistent and scalable self-tests that remain fully aligned with the NEM Life brand and positioning.\n\n## A3 - How the self-test works\n\n### Step 1 - Test entry & start state\nDefault layout of a self-test. For reference, the overall structure is conceptually inspired by established online self-tests such as the \"Depression Test\" on PsychologyToday.com.\nKey elements:\nA short, clear introduction explaining the purpose of the test\nAn indication of test length, including number of questions and estimated completion time\nA brief explanation of how to answer the questions, using a 1–5 scale from \"Strongly disagree\" to \"Strongly agree\"\n\n### Step 2 - Questions\nAfter answering the first question, the page scrolls smoothly to the next question within the same page, creating a natural and uninterrupted test flow without explicit navigation steps.\nEach question is scored on a scale from 1 to 5.\nThe total score is calculated by summing all question scores.\nAt the end of the test, the total score determines which result category the participant falls into. The number of categories is defined per test.\nFor an overview of all questions, see section 5 below.\n\n### Step 3 - Submission\nThe submit button is disabled by default and is only activated once the last question has been answered. After submission, the user is redirected to a dedicated result page displaying their outcome and next steps.\n\n### Step 4 - Test outcome\nThe test result page presents the outcome using two core elements:\nA visual diagram indicating the user's individual score (nice to have, not required).\nThe final score (required).\n\n### Step 5 - CTA: Extended report\nIn contrast to the Psychology Today setup, a NEM TEST self-test includes an additional step: participants are offered the option to receive a more detailed extended report in PDF format.\nOriginal approach: OTP verification (Phase A)\nInstead of a verification link, NEM Life used a 6-digit OTP code. The participant stayed on the result page — no context switch, no redirect.\nProcess:\nThe participant enters their email address on the result page.\nAn automated email is sent containing a 6-digit OTP code (valid for 10 minutes).\nThe participant enters the OTP code in the form on the same page.\nUpon successful validation, the extended report (PDF) is sent to the participant.\nUpon requesting the extended report, the participant is added to the NEM Life mailing list, in accordance with explicit consent provided during the request process.\nThis OTP approach has been replaced in Phase B. See phase B for the current flow.\n\n## A4 - Tech stack & integrations\nEmail platform: MailerLite — all email delivery (report PDF, subscriber opt-in) is handled via MailerLite.\nAutomation layer: n8n — responsible for score processing, PDF delivery, and adding subscribers to MailerLite.\nReport generation: Anthropic API (Claude) — dynamically generates the personalised PDF report based on Anna's score profile.\nFrontend: Webflow — form logic and UX handling on the test and result pages.\nFor the technical implementation of the n8n and MailerLite integration, we may bring in an external freelance developer if needed.\n\n## A5 - List of questions\nQuestions in test order. Annotations (mechanism / dimension) are internal — do not appear in the test.\nIk denk vaak: \"Als ik dit nou maar goed doe, dan komt het wel goed.\" — Valse Hoop / gedachte\nAls iets in een relatie of op werk misgaat, ben ik de eerste die denkt dat het aan mij ligt. — Zelfafwijzing / gedrag\nIk stel beslissingen of dingen die ik eigenlijk wil doen langer uit dan logisch is. — Emotionele Verdoving / gedrag\nIk betrap mezelf erop dat ik streng oordeel over hoe anderen dingen doen. — Valse Macht / gedachte\nIk vermijd situaties die spanning oproepen, ook als ik eigenlijk wel zou willen. — Angst / gedrag\nIk blijf mijn best doen om iets of iemand naar mijn hand te zetten, ook als ik weet dat het niet gaat lukken. — Valse Hoop / gedrag\nAls ik moe of overweldigd ben, zegt iets in mij: \"Ik kan dit niet aan.\" — Zelfafwijzing / gedachte\nMijn standaardreactie als er iets gebeurt is: \"Maakt niet uit, het komt wel goed.\" — Emotionele Verdoving / gedachte\nAls iemand iets doet wat me raakt, ervaar ik dat al snel als een persoonlijke aanval en ga ik er fel tegenin. — Valse Macht / gedrag\nBij iets nieuws of onbekends ga ik in mijn hoofd direct naar wat er mis zou kunnen gaan. — Angst / gedachte\nIk voel een drive in mijn lichaam - gejaagd, hoog, ik kan niet stil zitten als er nog iets opgelost moet worden. — Valse Hoop / lichaam\nNa een gesprek dat niet lekker liep, blijf ik uren of dagen malen over wat ik fout deed. — Zelfafwijzing / situationeel\nIn situaties die me eigenlijk zouden moeten raken, merk ik nauwelijks iets op in mijn lichaam - alsof ik op afstand sta van mijn eigen leven. — Emotionele Verdoving / lichaam\nOp het moment dat ik me aangevallen voel, voel ik mijn lichaam aanspannen - mijn kaken, mijn schouders, mijn vuisten, alsof ik me acuut wil verdedigen. — Valse Macht / lichaam\nIn spannende situaties voel ik mijn lichaam terugdeinzen - een verkramping, het gevoel dat ik ergens van weg wil. — Angst / lichaam\nAls de sfeer dreigt om te slaan, doe ik extra mijn best en pas ik me aan om het goed te houden. — Valse Hoop / situationeel\nAls iets misgaat voel ik mezelf wegzakken - mijn energie verdwijnt en alles wordt zwaar. — Zelfafwijzing / lichaam\nAls anderen om mij heen sterk reageren op een emotionele gebeurtenis, blijf ik vanbinnen vaak vlak. — Emotionele Verdoving / situationeel\nAls iemand dichtbij iets niet doet zoals ik wil, voel ik irritatie of boosheid die maar niet weggaat. — Valse Macht / situationeel\nAls ik iets moet doen wat goed voor me is maar me angst geeft, kies ik vaak voor wat veilig voelt. — Angst / situationeel\nScore mapping:\nValse Hoop: questions 1, 6, 11, 16\nZelfafwijzing: questions 2, 7, 12, 17\nEmotionele Verdoving: questions 3, 8, 13, 18\nValse Macht: questions 4, 9, 14, 19\nAngst: questions 5, 10, 15, 20"